which was on the
future of food, we

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:44.525
had a whole chapter on why
population growth matters.

00:39:44.525 --> 00:39:46.900
AUDIENCE: I think this probably
fits into building cities

00:39:46.900 --> 00:39:48.910
around people, not cars.

00:39:48.910 --> 00:39:51.050
But I'm curious if you
can share some stories

00:39:51.050 --> 00:39:54.640
around transportation
and maybe some light

00:39:54.640 --> 00:39:57.480
at the end of the tunnel
of what that's looking.

00:39:57.480 --> 00:39:58.980
Any projects that
are happening that

00:39:58.980 --> 00:40:02.820
will help transform some
of that [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:02.820 --> 00:40:04.140
ANDREW STEER: Yes.

00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:08.170
We have quite a large
transportation program

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:14.010
in about 40 cities in
the emerging world.

00:40:14.010 --> 00:40:16.770
There have been some revolutions
that don't sound very exciting,

00:40:16.770 --> 00:40:20.030
but actually are, for example,
bus rapid transit, which

00:40:20.030 --> 00:40:22.540
is when you take
up part of the road

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:25.680
and you protect it for buses.

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:30.450
In places like Mexico City,
even Shanghai now, Bangalore,

00:40:30.450 --> 00:40:32.020
places like that,
you're actually

00:40:32.020 --> 00:40:34.210
seeing amazing impacts.

00:40:34.210 --> 00:40:36.580
Now 200 cities have that.

00:40:36.580 --> 00:40:40.820
And what we show is that
it costs about 1/10 what

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:44.600
an underground metro
would cost but has

00:40:44.600 --> 00:40:49.640
90% of the benefits in
terms of time saved.

00:40:49.640 --> 00:40:51.480
And what we've seen
in Mexico City,

00:40:51.480 --> 00:40:55.720
for example, where poor people
are living on the periphery.

00:40:55.720 --> 00:40:58.430
Took 3 hours to get to work
in the morning, three hours

00:40:58.430 --> 00:40:59.420
to get home.

00:40:59.420 --> 00:41:02.220
So they had to leave at like
5 o'clock in the morning,

00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:04.382
didn't get home till
9 o'clock at night.

00:41:04.382 --> 00:41:06.215
Never saw their children,
couldn't help them

00:41:06.215 --> 00:41:07.270
with their homework.

00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:09.380
I mean really sort of
tragic that we've now

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:12.550
seen that cut by almost
an hour just introducing

00:41:12.550 --> 00:41:14.980
some modern techniques.

00:41:14.980 --> 00:41:18.410
But at the end of the day,
these are political choices

00:41:18.410 --> 00:41:23.050
as to whether or not leaders
have the courage to say,

00:41:23.050 --> 00:41:26.970
I'm going to put money into
public transportation that

00:41:26.970 --> 00:41:29.040
benefits all the citizens.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:33.300
Or am I going to put it in roads
that, in developing countries,

00:41:33.300 --> 00:41:35.040
benefit the top 10%.

00:41:35.040 --> 00:41:37.230
So you've got this real
tragedy in many countries

00:41:37.230 --> 00:41:40.960
where you see people sitting
in air-conditioned cars

00:41:40.960 --> 00:41:41.920
going down the street.

00:41:41.920 --> 00:41:44.150
Although now, they're
being stuck in traffic,

00:41:44.150 --> 00:41:47.340
while the poor people are having
to change buses four times.

00:41:47.340 --> 00:41:49.840
And the buses get stuck
just the same way,

00:41:49.840 --> 00:41:52.270
so they take even longer.

00:41:52.270 --> 00:41:54.140
Very interesting
question will be--

00:41:54.140 --> 00:41:56.690
and it's hotly debated
among environmentalists--

00:41:56.690 --> 00:41:59.380
is self-driving cars,
which obviously Google

00:41:59.380 --> 00:42:01.330
is the leader in.

00:42:01.330 --> 00:42:04.990
The question is from
sustainability standpoint,

00:42:04.990 --> 00:42:06.320
good or bad?

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:09.920
It's good, clearly, in that cars
will move more smoothly, more

00:42:09.920 --> 00:42:12.440
efficiently, and
obviously in a much less

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:14.910
polluting sort of way,
less stopping and starting.

00:42:14.910 --> 00:42:17.687
And of course, that will
be electric in time.

00:42:17.687 --> 00:42:19.270
But some are saying,
well, is it going

00:42:19.270 --> 00:42:23.350
to get in the way of
public transportation.

00:42:23.350 --> 00:42:25.190
I don't think it needs
to at all actually.

00:42:25.190 --> 00:42:26.930
I mean I think
there should still

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:29.560
be a way of combining the two.

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:35.590
But there does need to be
the kind of bold action

00:42:35.590 --> 00:42:40.660
that cities like London
took, where, for example-- I

00:42:40.660 --> 00:42:41.770
grew up in London.

00:42:41.770 --> 00:42:44.360
I used to drive into
London all the time,

00:42:44.360 --> 00:42:45.790
all ride into central London.

00:42:45.790 --> 00:42:47.336
That's how we used to get there.

00:42:47.336 --> 00:42:51.910
And about 15 years ago,
the government said,

00:42:51.910 --> 00:42:54.959
we're going to charge to go
into the middle of London.

00:42:54.959 --> 00:42:56.500
We're going to charge
electronically.

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:59.460
So as you pass through
this, you get eight pounds

00:42:59.460 --> 00:43:01.320
taken off your credit card.

00:43:01.320 --> 00:43:03.340
Interestingly, that's
not very much money.

00:43:03.340 --> 00:43:05.980
It's not the money
that changes this.

00:43:05.980 --> 00:43:08.670
But because of that
psychological shift--

00:43:08.670 --> 00:43:11.030
I just lived three years
in the suburb of London.

00:43:11.030 --> 00:43:13.590
Never once in that three
years did I drive into London.

00:43:13.590 --> 00:43:16.850
And I would die before I
ever drive into London again.

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:21.310
I will never ever drive a
car in the center of London.

00:43:21.310 --> 00:43:23.707
How could that switch happen?

00:43:23.707 --> 00:43:25.040
And that's what needs to happen.

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:27.520
And Beijing now has
asked us to help

00:43:27.520 --> 00:43:30.420
them think through a
similar system for Beijing.

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:32.910
And there's a lot of
complicated issues of technology

00:43:32.910 --> 00:43:36.540
and, more important, political
acceptability of course.

00:43:36.540 --> 00:43:41.030
So we're simply doing the
technical work with them,

00:43:41.030 --> 00:43:43.180
taking them to a place like
Stockholm and Singapore

00:43:43.180 --> 00:43:46.270
and London and showing
them how to do that.

00:43:46.270 --> 00:43:48.360
I understand that Mayor
Bloomberg in New York, who

00:43:48.360 --> 00:43:51.000
obviously was a
wonderful mayor-- this

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:53.510
was the one, I
think, sort of regret

00:43:53.510 --> 00:43:57.680
that he tried to move forward
on congestion pricing,

00:43:57.680 --> 00:43:58.710
as it's called.

00:43:58.710 --> 00:44:02.040
And couldn't get the
political support for it

00:44:02.040 --> 00:44:03.430
because it is difficult.

00:44:03.430 --> 00:44:04.070
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:44:04.070 --> 00:44:07.500
On the food loss and waste,
besides the agricultural remote

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:09.180
sensing, what
other opportunities

00:44:09.180 --> 00:44:10.992
do you see for
applications of technology?

00:44:10.992 --> 00:44:13.200
And what are some things
that us sitting in this room

00:44:13.200 --> 00:44:14.480
can be doing?

00:44:14.480 --> 00:44:15.490
ANDREW STEER: Wow.

00:44:15.490 --> 00:44:16.380
Good question.

00:44:16.380 --> 00:44:19.980
Actually, I haven't thought
about that, and I'd have to.

00:44:19.980 --> 00:44:27.740
I think for rich
countries-- Tesco

00:44:27.740 --> 00:44:30.770
just came out with its
annual statement and said,

00:44:30.770 --> 00:44:32.240
we want to come clean.

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:37.757
55,000 tons of food in
our care was wasted.

00:44:37.757 --> 00:44:39.840
That's not when you take
it home, you don't eat it

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:41.230
or your kids throw it away.

00:44:41.230 --> 00:44:43.837
It's within the care of Tesco.

00:44:43.837 --> 00:44:45.545
And they said, we want
to be transparent,

00:44:45.545 --> 00:44:46.920
and every year we're going to.

00:44:46.920 --> 00:44:48.590
So the question is,
what do they do?

00:44:48.590 --> 00:44:51.980
I mean they need-- which
they're doing and so is Walmart.

00:44:51.980 --> 00:44:57.790
They need very sophisticated
logistical, just-in-time

00:44:57.790 --> 00:44:59.470
inventories and so on.

00:44:59.470 --> 00:45:01.830
I mean there's just lots
of tricks that they do.

00:45:01.830 --> 00:45:08.400
So to the extent that that
requires the kind of high tech

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:12.780
sophisticated support
that a company like Google

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:15.970
could provide, that's one.

00:45:15.970 --> 00:45:18.440
With regard to
developing countries,

00:45:18.440 --> 00:45:23.530
I think that-- I mean the
issue there is for 20-30 years,

00:45:23.530 --> 00:45:26.190
we've all known that it's
a terrible, terrible waste

00:45:26.190 --> 00:45:29.720
to see these poor farmers
slaving and getting

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:31.600
yields which are not very high.

00:45:31.600 --> 00:45:33.360
And then half of
the food sometimes

00:45:33.360 --> 00:45:35.640
is lost simply because
they don't have storage.

00:45:35.640 --> 00:45:40.820
There are new technologies now
that enable that to be kept.

00:45:40.820 --> 00:45:44.850
And of course, the existence
of distributed power

00:45:44.850 --> 00:45:48.320
enables for certain crops'
power to be used just

00:45:48.320 --> 00:45:51.090
to keep the temperature a
little bit cooler, which

00:45:51.090 --> 00:45:58.460
can dramatically affect the
sustainability of the food

00:45:58.460 --> 00:45:59.960
for another month or so.

00:45:59.960 --> 00:46:00.960
Do you know what I mean?

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:02.860
And then obviously, the
more sophisticated crops

00:46:02.860 --> 00:46:04.030
is all about cold storage.

00:46:04.030 --> 00:46:05.710
And there, again,
that comes into it.

00:46:05.710 --> 00:46:08.470
But the prediction--
I mean remote sensing

00:46:08.470 --> 00:46:11.320
is potentially
exceedingly important.

00:46:11.320 --> 00:46:15.730
If you can see what a crop is
going to be by remote sensing

00:46:15.730 --> 00:46:19.160
before the crop is harvested--
if two months before the crop

00:46:19.160 --> 00:46:22.460
is harvested you know it's
going to be a bumper crop,

00:46:22.460 --> 00:46:23.917
that has all kinds
of implications

00:46:23.917 --> 00:46:25.500
of how you're going
to store your food

00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:27.208
and how you're going
to get it to market.

00:46:27.208 --> 00:46:29.166
And it enables you
to get a start-- do

00:46:29.166 --> 00:46:31.430
you know what I mean-- to
get us a start on things.

00:46:31.430 --> 00:46:35.479
So there are some exciting
possibilities I think.

00:46:35.479 --> 00:46:36.020
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:37.840
Thanks for speaking today.

00:46:37.840 --> 00:46:39.900
I think that major
players in sustainability

00:46:39.900 --> 00:46:43.360
are continually seeing
issues like social justice

00:46:43.360 --> 00:46:46.480
and public health
as really being

00:46:46.480 --> 00:46:48.840
central to environmental
sustainability, whereas that's

00:46:48.840 --> 00:46:50.880
been a little bit more
segmented in the past.

00:46:50.880 --> 00:46:53.847
And I wanted to know where you
think our key points of overlap

00:46:53.847 --> 00:46:55.430
that are going to
be really important,

00:46:55.430 --> 00:46:57.230
not just for environmental
sustainability,

00:46:57.230 --> 00:46:59.271
but issues of public
health, where we can sort of

00:46:59.271 --> 00:47:02.002
kill two birds with one stone.

00:47:02.002 --> 00:47:03.460
ANDREW STEER: Well,
I think, I mean

00:47:03.460 --> 00:47:08.120
if there's one truth
about environmental damage

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:11.890
is that, in almost
all situations--

00:47:11.890 --> 00:47:14.354
air pollution may be
an exception-- it hurts

00:47:14.354 --> 00:47:15.520
the poor more than the rich.

00:47:15.520 --> 00:47:18.660
In most environmental
problems, the rich

00:47:18.660 --> 00:47:22.750
are able, one way or the other,
to buy their way out of it.

00:47:22.750 --> 00:47:26.440
So most cities, if
you look at them,

00:47:26.440 --> 00:47:31.220
historically, the poor people
live downwind and down river

00:47:31.220 --> 00:47:32.010
often.

00:47:32.010 --> 00:47:35.640
So in London-- say, my city,
but it's true of all cities--

00:47:35.640 --> 00:47:37.970
east end of London,
always the poor area.

00:47:37.970 --> 00:47:39.330
West end of London?

00:47:39.330 --> 00:47:40.040
Rich people.

00:47:40.040 --> 00:47:40.540
Why?

00:47:40.540 --> 00:47:43.280
Because the west end of
London, air is cleaner,

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:44.660
water is cleaner, and so on.

00:47:44.660 --> 00:47:45.660
Do you know what I mean?

00:47:45.660 --> 00:47:47.460
I'll pollute you down.

00:47:47.460 --> 00:47:50.910
There's a general truth
that if you address

00:47:50.910 --> 00:47:55.260
environmental issues smartly,
you will benefit the poor

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:58.240
and you will advance the
cause of social justice.

00:47:58.240 --> 00:48:01.640
And climate change is
clearly the case in point--

00:48:01.640 --> 00:48:03.020
the most dramatic case.

00:48:03.020 --> 00:48:05.170
I mean there are
many studies now

00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:08.290
that show the impacts of
climate change on the poor

00:48:08.290 --> 00:48:10.670
will be really desperate.

00:48:10.670 --> 00:48:12.620
That's why one of
the things that we do

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:18.680
is we run a network of
300 organizations in 50

00:48:18.680 --> 00:48:23.110
countries dedicated to
giving citizens the right

00:48:23.110 --> 00:48:24.620
to have environmental data.

00:48:24.620 --> 00:48:26.270
It's called the
Access Initiative.

00:48:26.270 --> 00:48:27.496
And we publish something.

00:48:27.496 --> 00:48:28.870
We've just started
to publish it.

00:48:28.870 --> 00:48:30.411
We're going to do
it every year, what

00:48:30.411 --> 00:48:32.710
we call an environmental
democracy index.

00:48:32.710 --> 00:48:34.870
And what that does
is it says, look,

00:48:34.870 --> 00:48:39.680
we think that everybody has
the right to know, at least,

00:48:39.680 --> 00:48:42.020
and to engage in decisions.

00:48:42.020 --> 00:48:45.450
So for example,
does a country have

00:48:45.450 --> 00:48:50.490
user-friendly data on air
pollution in the capital city?

00:48:50.490 --> 00:48:54.010
China now is a leader in that.

00:48:54.010 --> 00:48:55.900
They certainly
weren't 10 years ago.

00:48:55.900 --> 00:48:59.405
But our staff in China
wake up every morning.

00:48:59.405 --> 00:49:01.780
They check on their smartphone
what the air pollution is.

00:49:01.780 --> 00:49:04.070
And that, they decide
whether to putting a mask on

00:49:04.070 --> 00:49:06.620
to go do their
work, so to speak.

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:11.000
So environmental democracy
means that all citizens

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.220
have the right to
get information

00:49:13.220 --> 00:49:16.370
and the right to engage
in decision making.

00:49:16.370 --> 00:49:20.050
So I think the links
are incredibly close.

00:49:20.050 --> 00:49:21.800
REBECCA MOORE: I know
you have a question,

00:49:21.800 --> 00:49:24.290
but if you don't mind,
I'd like to ask one.

00:49:24.290 --> 00:49:28.640
There's a story that is in
the news about the extinction

00:49:28.640 --> 00:49:29.994
crisis.

00:49:29.994 --> 00:49:30.660
Is this working?

00:49:30.660 --> 00:49:31.970
Now it is.

00:49:31.970 --> 00:49:35.000
That there's an accelerating
loss of plant and animal

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:38.590
species, hundreds if not
thousands of species going

00:49:38.590 --> 00:49:41.360
extinct accelerating rate.

00:49:41.360 --> 00:49:44.590
And it seems to be due to
climate change and habitat

00:49:44.590 --> 00:49:45.450
loss.

00:49:45.450 --> 00:49:48.190
I think something like
90% of endangered species

00:49:48.190 --> 00:49:49.920
are dependent on forests.

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:52.530
And so as forests
are cut down, we

00:49:52.530 --> 00:49:54.990
are eliminating these species.

00:49:54.990 --> 00:49:58.130
E.O. Wilson is apparently coming
out with something [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:58.130 --> 00:49:59.250
50% of nature.

00:49:59.250 --> 00:50:02.040
He's like a leading biologist,
ecologist at Harvard.

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:04.450
That the idea is we
can't save all of nature,

00:50:04.450 --> 00:50:07.410
but can we agree to
save 50% of nature

00:50:07.410 --> 00:50:09.800
and agree on where that
is and draw the line?

00:50:09.800 --> 00:50:12.852
And Eric Dinerstein of WRI I
believe is involved with this.

00:50:12.852 --> 00:50:14.560
This book is going to
come out this year.

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:19.185
Anyway, so what is your, what
is WRI's position on all that?

00:50:19.185 --> 00:50:21.750
ANDREW STEER: That's
a brilliant question.

00:50:21.750 --> 00:50:27.820
One of the real puzzles is,
why is biodiversity and species

00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:29.940
loss not a big political issue?

00:50:29.940 --> 00:50:31.690
I mean it's really interesting.

00:50:31.690 --> 00:50:36.660
I was at the original
Rio Earth Summit in 1992.

00:50:36.660 --> 00:50:41.250
And there we saw two
treaties being signed--

00:50:41.250 --> 00:50:43.390
climate change, biodiversity.

00:50:43.390 --> 00:50:45.360
In the next five
years, biodiversity

00:50:45.360 --> 00:50:47.830
was a much hotter issue
than climate change.

00:50:47.830 --> 00:50:51.030
I mean it was really a
buzzy important issue.

00:50:51.030 --> 00:50:53.147
And in the last 15 years,
it's totally fallen

00:50:53.147 --> 00:50:54.980
off the agenda, which
is really interesting,

00:50:54.980 --> 00:50:57.146
whilst climate change
actually has done rather well.

00:50:57.146 --> 00:50:59.850
And even the stories I tell,
you notice, they're about that.

00:50:59.850 --> 00:51:03.790
So I don't know whether E.O.
Wilson's 50% is the right

00:51:03.790 --> 00:51:07.980
or not, but we absolutely
need to demonstrate

00:51:07.980 --> 00:51:10.370
how the kinds of things
we're talking about

00:51:10.370 --> 00:51:11.570
will affect biodiversity.

00:51:11.570 --> 00:51:15.360
I mean our view is, quite
frankly, that we are hoping--

00:51:15.360 --> 00:51:17.160
and we're working
with IUCN in the lead

00:51:17.160 --> 00:51:20.390
up to the big IUCN
conference in Hawaii

00:51:20.390 --> 00:51:24.060
later on this year, which
they have every three years.

00:51:24.060 --> 00:51:28.380
We're hoping to get
some more political buzz

00:51:28.380 --> 00:51:29.860
around biodiversity.

00:51:29.860 --> 00:51:34.390
But in the meantime,
quite frankly,

00:51:34.390 --> 00:51:38.770
the policies of smart
cities-- cutting food waste,

00:51:38.770 --> 00:51:43.640
addressing knowledge on forests,
addressing supply chains

00:51:43.640 --> 00:51:46.990
on palm oil and soy--
do you know what I mean?

00:51:46.990 --> 00:51:49.390
Those other ways,
practical ways,

00:51:49.390 --> 00:51:52.760
even though you don't say
that's why we're doing them.

00:51:52.760 --> 00:51:55.020
But it would be great.

00:51:55.020 --> 00:51:57.390
Eric Dinerstein is just
this wonderful fellow.

00:51:57.390 --> 00:52:02.345
And we're using Global Forest
Watch now for tiger protection.

00:52:02.345 --> 00:52:03.922
It's fabulous.

00:52:03.922 --> 00:52:05.130
That's such a great question.

00:52:05.130 --> 00:52:07.505
REBECCA MOORE: I think I have
time for one more question.

00:52:07.505 --> 00:52:09.550
You've been patiently waiting.

00:52:09.550 --> 00:52:11.070
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:11.070 --> 00:52:11.570
Yeah.

00:52:11.570 --> 00:52:12.580
Thanks.

00:52:12.580 --> 00:52:16.590
So I like eating meat, you know?

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:17.420
I enjoy it.

00:52:17.420 --> 00:52:20.510
But I think I'm lucky
enough to be in a position

00:52:20.510 --> 00:52:26.270
where if I didn't have to eat
meat or meat were restricted,

00:52:26.270 --> 00:52:28.460
I would be fine not eating
meat-- being vegetarian.

00:52:31.250 --> 00:52:36.610
You mentioned food waste and
the sort of ecological impact,

00:52:36.610 --> 00:52:40.320
but I'm wondering whether the
reduction of meat consumption

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:42.830
is something that comes
up in these conversations.

00:52:42.830 --> 00:52:46.700
I mean we know it contributes
to global warming in a huge way,

00:52:46.700 --> 00:52:49.840
especially in
affluent nations where

00:52:49.840 --> 00:52:51.957
people don't have to eat meat.

00:52:51.957 --> 00:52:53.790
Is that something that's
being talked about?

00:52:53.790 --> 00:52:55.880
Is that a part of the
conversation at all?

00:52:55.880 --> 00:52:56.671
ANDREW STEER: Yeah.

00:52:56.671 --> 00:52:59.200
So it's a really important
part of the conversation,

00:52:59.200 --> 00:53:01.820
and it's a really good question.

00:53:01.820 --> 00:53:07.550
Why do humans change
their behavior?

00:53:07.550 --> 00:53:11.460
Why do they sometimes not
change for a long time and then

00:53:11.460 --> 00:53:14.220
suddenly they will switch?

00:53:14.220 --> 00:53:19.150
And there is a very important
field of psychology,

00:53:19.150 --> 00:53:22.349
and commercial psychology,
that has learned a lot.

00:53:22.349 --> 00:53:23.890
And so what we're
doing is setting up

00:53:23.890 --> 00:53:27.630
a small lab precisely
to look at the issue of,

00:53:27.630 --> 00:53:31.930
what it would take to get
people to eat less meat?

00:53:31.930 --> 00:53:33.510
And part of that
is, for example,

00:53:33.510 --> 00:53:38.030
even if you can get the
leading providers of food

00:53:38.030 --> 00:53:41.020
in supermarkets to position
things differently,

00:53:41.020 --> 00:53:44.950
and little things like that, and
the whole science of nudge now.

00:53:44.950 --> 00:53:46.490
That's really what it's about.

00:53:46.490 --> 00:53:49.570
How do you not sort
of preach at them--

00:53:49.570 --> 00:53:51.830
I mean interestingly,
the reason there's

00:53:51.830 --> 00:53:54.950
been this massive shift
in smoking, turns out,

00:53:54.950 --> 00:53:58.680
actually, is not only or not
mainly because the government

00:53:58.680 --> 00:54:00.590
has passed rules actually.

00:54:00.590 --> 00:54:03.330
It's much more to do
with social pressure,

00:54:03.330 --> 00:54:05.690
and it's to do with nudging.

00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:06.670
It's labeling.

00:54:06.670 --> 00:54:08.100
It's all things like that.

00:54:08.100 --> 00:54:09.892
So we believe this is
very, very important.

